      {
        "title": "Summary of gap priorities",
        "content": "| Priority | Module | Why |\n|---|---|---|\n| 1 | `models.parse_posted_at` | Silent-failure date parsing feeds the recency filter directly; wrong parsing = wrong drops |\n| 2 | `store.diff` | Core dedup correctness; a bug here duplicates or silently drops jobs |\n| 3 | `fetchers.py` parsers | Hand-parsed against undocumented APIs (Google `ds:1`, D.E. Shaw/Two Sigma regex scraping) — most likely to break on upstream changes, easiest to catch with fixtures |\n| 4 | `fetchers._request` retry + `fetch_all` isolation | The \"don't let one source kill the run\" contract has no regression test |\n| 5 | `notify.dispatch` isolation | Same failure-isolation contract, untested |\n| 6 | `filters.match` cutoff/keyword logic | Business-rule correctness, plus one real gap found (`max_age_days: 0` treated as disabled) |\n| 7 | `pipeline.run` | Integration test tying fetch→filter→dedup→notify together |\n| 8 | `agent.py` helpers | Lower risk (internal tooling), but `_normalize_ats` and watermark-truncation logic are non-trivial enough to deserve coverage |\n\n**Missing integration test entirely:** there's no test that runs the full pipeline against a live-shaped fixture (e.g., record one real Greenhouse/Lever response, replay it through `fetch_all` → `filter_jobs` → `Store.diff` → `dispatch`) to catch schema drift across the seam boundaries. Worth adding once the unit layer above exists.",
